section.t:
The present document is essentially a problem position document.
More precisely, the contributions are twofold:

	 we provide a taxonomy of router behavior with respect to ICMP;
	 we provide examples taken from real world experiments, using existing tools
	to illustrate the previous discussion and taxonomy;

We can define three different paths ():
the initial forward path: this is the path between S and R; the final forward path: this is the path between R and D; the ICMP return path: This is the path taken by ICMP packets destined to S and generated either by R, or by a router on the final forward path, or by D itself, and that go through R (this is not necessarily the case);
It is important to note that the initial forward path up to R and the return ICMP path from R are not necessarily identical since routers often have different forwarding rules for each direction. The forward initial or final paths also potentially depend on the nature of the initial packet protocol, since routers often use protocol dependent forwarding rules. Finally, it is important to note that there are potentially as many ICMP return paths as there are routers on the forwarding path.

We then distinguish three ICMP-related abilities for traffic from S to D:
Ability A1: "R forwards ICMP packets destined to D on the final forward path when appropriate": upon receiving an ICMP packet from S, after A0 processing, when appropriate, does R forward it to D?
Ability A2: "ICMP packet generation at R": if an event requiring the generation of an ICMP packet occurs, does R forge an ICMP packet and does R return it to S, regardless of whether this packet arrives to S or not? For instance this ICMP packet can result from an IPv4 TTL/IPv6 Hop Limit field that decrements to 0 during the forwarding of a packet received on the incoming forward path;
Ability A3: "correct ICMP return path from R": when an ICMP packet is sent back to S from R (when it is generated by R) or through R (when it is generated by a router on the final forward path, D included), does this packet reach S? It not necessarily the case, even if R can generate ICMP packets, e.g., because of ICMP filtering rules;

